{{coord|35|42|55.56|N|139|47|32.41|E|type:landmark_region:JP|display=title}} {{Infobox theatre | name = Asakusa International Theater | image = Asakusa Kokusai Gekijo - 1930s.jpg| image_size = | image_alt = A large theater building with Japanese language signs on it. | caption = | image_map = | map_caption = | latd= | longd= | pushpin_map = | pushpin_map_caption= | address = | city = [[Asakusa]], [[Tokyo]] | country = Japan | designation = | latitude = | longitude = | architect = | owner = | tenant = | operator = [[Shochiku]] | capacity = 3860 | type = | opened = 1937 | reopened = | yearsactive = | rebuilt = | closed = | demolished = 1982 | othernames = | production = | currentuse = | website = }} {{Nihongo|'''Asakusa International Theater'''|浅草国際劇場|Asakusa Kokusai Gekijō}} was a 3860-seat [[theater (building)|theater]] located in [[Asakusa]], [[Taitō, Tokyo]], Japan, which was used for concerts and theatrical performances. It opened in 1937 and was closed in 1982. It has since been demolished. It was owned and operated by [[Shochiku]] and primarily featured the {{Nihongo|Shōchiku Shōjo Kagekidan|松竹少女歌劇団}}, an all-woman musical theatre troupe.<ref name=Matsudo>{{cite web|last=Nemoto|first=Keisuke|title=華やかなりし国際劇場とSKD（上）|url=http://www.matsuyomi.co.jp/showashi/showashi_BN_005.html|work=Matsudo Yomiuri|accessdate=30 March 2013}}</ref> The SKD often appeared in a double bill with a film. Other artists that performed at the theater include [[King Crimson]] and [[Whitesnake]].<ref name=Matsudo />
